Q1) Probability of Shooting at a Target

1. Uniform by area
Area of disk = 100π  
Area of ring (within 1 of boundary) = 100π – 81π = 19π  
P(A) = 19π/100π = 0.19

2. Uniform radius
Distance from center uniform [0,10]  
P(A) = (10-9)/(10-0) = 0.10

3. Why different?
Uniform by area gives more weight to outer rings (more area).  
Uniform radius treats all distances equally.


Q2) Bertrand's Paradox

Model 1 – Random endpoints
Pick two points uniformly on circumference. Chord longer than triangle side if central angle > 120°.  
P = 1/3

Model 2 – Random midpoint
Pick midpoint uniformly inside circle. Chord longer than triangle side if midpoint lies inside circle of radius R/2.  
P = (π(R/2)²) / (πR²) = 1/4

Model 3 – Random radial point
Pick distance from center uniform [0,R], draw perpendicular chord. Chord longer than triangle side if distance < R/2.  
P = (R/2)/R = 1/2

Why different?
Each model defines "random chord" differently — endpoints, midpoint, or radial distance. No single answer without specifying the method.



Q8) Probability of Being a Girl?

A family has two children. Each child equally likely to be boy (B) or girl (G), independent.

Find: P(both girls | at least one girl)

Sample space: Ω = {BB, BG, GB, GG}, each with probability 1/4.

Events:  
A = both girls = {GG}  
B = at least one girl = {BG, GB, GG}

Calculation:
P(A|B) = (1/4) / (3/4) = 1/3

Answer: 1/3 ≈ 33.3%



Q9) Information Available in a Discrete Random Variable

Ω = {G₁, G₂, D₁, D₂}  
P(G₁)=0.50, P(G₂)=0.20, P(D₁)=0.10, P(D₂)=0.20

1. Probability space
(Ω, ℱ, P) with ℱ = 𝒫(Ω) (all subsets)

2. σ(X)
X = 0 for good (G₁,G₂), X = 1 for defective (D₁,D₂)  
σ(X) = {∅, {G₁,G₂}, {D₁,D₂}, Ω}

3. σ(Y)
Y = 1(G₁), 2(G₂), 3(D₁), 4(D₂)  
σ(Y) = 𝒫(Ω) (all 16 subsets)

4. σ(X) ⊆ σ(Y)
σ(X) subsets are contained in σ(Y). Y contains more info because it distinguishes machines.

5. Marginal distribution of X
P(X=0) = 0.70, P(X=1) = 0.30

6. Marginal distribution of Y
P(Y=1)=0.50, P(Y=2)=0.20, P(Y=3)=0.10, P(Y=4)=0.20

7. Joint probabilities
P(X=0,Y=1)=0.50, P(X=0,Y=2)=0.20, P(X=1,Y=3)=0.10, P(X=1,Y=4)=0.20

8. Conditional probabilities
P(X=1|Y=3)=1, P(X=1|Y=4)=1  
P(Y=3|X=1)=1/3, P(Y=4|X=1)=2/3

9. Interpretation
Conditioning on X: know good/defective but not machine  
Conditioning on Y: know everything with certainty

10. Information difference
σ(Y) has machine info that σ(X) lacks. σ(X) has no extra info beyond σ(Y).

