12. Shannon Entropy
Marginal entropy H(X):
H(X) = – [P(X=0) log₂ P(X=0) + P(X=1) log₂ P(X=1)]
= – [0.70 × log₂(0.70) + 0.30 × log₂(0.30)]
= – [0.70 × (-0.5146) + 0.30 × (-1.737)]
= – [-0.3602 - 0.5211] = **0.881 bits

Marginal entropy H(Y):
H(Y) = – Σ P(Y=y) log₂ P(Y=y)
= – [0.50 log₂(0.50) + 0.20 log₂(0.20) + 0.10 log₂(0.10) + 0.20 log₂(0.20)]
= – [0.50×(-1) + 0.20×(-2.322) + 0.10×(-3.322) + 0.20×(-2.322)]
= – [-0.5 - 0.4644 - 0.3322 - 0.4644]
= – [-1.761] = 1.761 bits

Joint entropy H(X,Y):
Since Y determines X completely, H(X,Y) = H(Y) = 1.761 bits

Conditional entropy H(X|Y):
H(X|Y) = H(X,Y) – H(Y) = 1.761 – 1.761 = 0 bits

Conditional entropy H(Y|X):
H(Y|X) = H(X,Y) – H(X) = 1.761 – 0.881 = 0.880 bits

Interpretation:
- H(X|Y) = 0: Knowing Y tells you X with certainty
- H(Y|X) = 0.88: Knowing X, there is still uncertainty about which machine produced the item



Q10) Information Available in Continuous Random Variables

T ∼ N(0,1), P ∼ N(0,4), independent. Y = (T,P), X = T.

1. Probability space
Ω = ℝ², ℱ = ℬ(ℝ²) (Borel σ-algebra), P = probability measure induced by joint density:
f_{T,P}(t,p) = (1/(4π)) exp(-t²/2 - p²/8)

2. σ-algebra generated by X
σ(X) = { X⁻¹(B) : B ∈ ℬ(ℝ) } = { A × ℝ : A ∈ ℬ(ℝ) }
All subsets of ℝ² that depend only on t-coordinate.

3. σ-algebra generated by Y
σ(Y) = { Y⁻¹(B) : B ∈ ℬ(ℝ²) } = ℬ(ℝ²) (all Borel sets in ℝ²)
Because Y is the identity function.

4. σ(X) ⊆ σ(Y)
Every set of the form A × ℝ is a Borel set in ℝ². Therefore σ(X) ⊂ σ(Y).
Y contains more info because knowing (t,p) tells you t, but knowing t alone doesn't tell you p.

5. Marginal density of X
X ∼ N(0,1)
f_X(x) = (1/√(2π)) exp(-x²/2)

6. Marginal density of Y
Y has joint density: f_Y(t,p) = (1/(4π)) exp(-t²/2 - p²/8)

7. Probabilities
P(X ≤ 0) = Φ(0) = 0.5
P(X > 1) = 1 - Φ(1) = 1 - 0.8413 = 0.1587
P(Y ∈ (-∞,0] × ℝ) = P(X ≤ 0) = 0.5
P(Y ∈ [-1,1] × [-2,2]) = P(-1 ≤ T ≤ 1) × P(-2 ≤ P ≤ 2)
= [Φ(1) - Φ(-1)] × [Φ(2/2) - Φ(-2/2)]
= (0.8413 - 0.1587) × (Φ(1) - Φ(-1))
= 0.6826 × 0.6826 = 0.466

8. Conditional distribution of X given Y = (t,p)
Given Y = (t,p), X = t is known exactly.
P(X ∈ A | Y = (t,p)) = 1 if t ∈ A, else 0.
Degenerate distribution at X = t.

9. Conditional distribution of Y given X = t
Given X = t, P ∼ N(0,4) independently.
Y | X=t is degenerate in t-coordinate (fixed at t), and P ∼ N(0,4) in p-coordinate.

10. Information difference
Conditioning on X: You know temperature deviation but not pressure.
Conditioning on Y: You know both temperature and pressure exactly. No uncertainty remains.

11. X = π₁ ∘ Y
π₁(t,p) = t, so π₁(Y(t,p)) = π₁(t,p) = t = X(t,p).
Since π₁ is measurable, X is a measurable function of Y. This implies σ(X) ⊆ σ(Y).

